B.akk=new A.c("White cannot take this Pawn. If he does, you can play Bx9a+.")
B.amd=new A.c("You may think P*7c will be equally good. In this case, however, White can play P6d, good defense.")
B.VW=A.a(s(["P*7b","B-5c","P-7a+","Bx7a","P*7e"]),t.s)
B.a8K=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 2-1:",B.VW,B.j)
B.O3=new A.p("lnb4nl/r5gk1/1p1p1gspp/p1s1ppp2/2P6/1S1PP4/PP1GSP1PP/1KG3RB1/LN5NL w 2p","Diagram 2-2")
B.al_=new A.c("If White plays B5c like above, he may be able to defend Black's P7a+, but after P7a+, Bx7a, Black can play P*7e, claiming the Silver for free.")
B.ahl=new A.c("After Black's P*7b, White may play P6d, which will launch the following moves: P7a+, N7c, +P8a. Thus, this is the least destructive position for White, but he will certainly lose the Lance.")
B.ajC=new A.c("Creation of a Tokin may not be powerful enough to lead to an overwhelming predominace at once, but it will certainly get you to a favorable position. This is the spirit of the proverb: The Tokin may seem slow, but is fast.")
B.Xe=A.a(s([B.KN,B.amH,B.aaC,B.akk,B.amd,B.a8K,B.O3,B.al_,B.ahl,B.ajC]),t.A)
B.acQ=new A.ar(B.Xe)
B.W_=A.a(s([B.adf,B.acQ]),t.l)
B.ao6=new A.bf(17,B.aN,"A Tokin is Faster Than You Think","Tokin no oso haya",B.W_)
B.alF=new A.c("It is extremely dangerous to start fighting with the King sitting on the original square.")
B.amE=new A.c("In Diagram 1, Black has already advanced a Silver onto 4f with his King in the original position. If he wants to launch an attack from here, how would he play?")
B.N_=new A.p("ln3k1nl/1r3bg2/p1ppsgspp/1p2ppp2/7P1/2PPPSP2/PPS2P2P/2G1G2R1/LNB1K2NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.VN=A.a(s(["P-3e","Px3e","Sx3e","P*3d","P-2d","Px2d","Sx2d","Sx2d","Bx2d","Bx2d","Rx2d"]),t.s)
B.a90=new A.Q(null,B.VN,B.j)
B.MG=new A.p("ln3k1nl/1r4g2/p1ppsg2p/1p2pppR1/9/2PPP4/PPS2P2P/2G1G4/LN2K2NL w BS2Pbsp","Diagram 2")
B.aeb=new A.c("So far, Black's climbing Silver appears to have made a point. But White has a devastating move to play here.")
B.a_r=A.a(s(["B*1e"]),t.s)
B.a8L=new A.Q(null,B.a_r,B.u)
B.amh=new A.c("You cannot be too careful when you have a sitting King. Black had to play K6i first in this case. Then the attack would have been successful.")
B.a0v=A.a(s([B.alF,B.amE,B.N_,B.a90,B.MG,B.aeb,B.a8L,B.amh]),t.A)
B.acj=new A.ar(B.a0v)
B.a3w=A.a(s([B.acj]),t.l)
B.aoy=new A.bf(18,B.bs,"Avoid a Sitting King","Igyoku wa sakeyo",B.a3w)
B.ah7=new A.c("This is one of the most important proverbs that I should say is something you should learn before actually playing a game.")
B.amp=new A.c("The Rook is by far the most important piece in offence, therefore being close to the Rook means close to the battlefield. The King had better be some distance away.")
B.agG=new A.c("Thus, one of the basics is that you should castle your King in the opposite direction to your Rook.")
B.ag6=new A.c("When you want to play the 4th file ranging Rook, begin with P7f, followed by P6f, and R6h. Then you go on to play K4h, K3h, and K2h, so that the Rook and the King sit left and right, safely apart.")
B.agw=new A.c("After that, you play S3h, G6i-5h, S7h. Now you have completed the Mino castle and about to be ready to move into the next phase. (Diagram 1)")
B.KR=new A.p("9/9/9/9/9/2PP5/PP2PPPPP/1BSRG1SK1/LN3G1NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.an_=new A.c("Above is how the traditional ranging Rook opening has been played. Recently, however, S3h is often played before the King is moved.")
B.agN=new A.c("Next, I'll show you how you should move your pieces when you want to play the Yagura opening: P7f, S6h, P6f, P5f, S4h.")
B.alI=new A.c("Then, you play G7h, K6i, G5h. (Diagram 2, the Crab-gakoi castle)")
B.N3=new A.p("9/9/9/9/9/2PPP4/PP3PPPP/1BGSGS1R1/LN1K3NL b -","Diagram 2")
B.agB=new A.c("The castle in Diagram 2 is called the Kani (crab) castle, which is strong against an attack from above. From here you can build a Yagura castle by playing S7g, G5h-6g.")
B.ae2=new A.c("There are many variations to build a Yagura, and you can be flexible. Just remember to move your generals diagonally.")
B.agk=new A.c("You still have to move your Bishop so that the King can safely sit in the Yagura castle. So you play, B7i, B6h, K7i, and K8h. (Diagram 3)")
B.Oe=new A.p("9/9/9/9/9/2PPP4/PPSG1PPPP/1KGB1S1R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 3")
B.afr=new A.c("There, the King is sitting safely in the Yagura castle far from the Rook.")
B.Xm=A.a(s([B.ah7,B.amp,B.agG,B.ag6,B.agw,B.KR,B.an_,B.agN,B.alI,B.N3,B.agB,B.ae2,B.agk,B.Oe,B.afr]),t.A)
B.acG=new A.ar(B.Xm)
B.Tk=A.a(s([B.acG]),t.l)
B.aoG=new A.bf(19,B.bs,"Don't Put King and Rook Close Together","Gyoku-hi sekkin su bekarazu",B.Tk)
B.agI=new A.c("You might have heard about how the Fujii system and the Crab Silver diverge from the basic formation. They can be very effective indeed when employed by a skillful hand. But I advise you to learn the basics first and then attempt the trickier lines.")
B.agl=new A.c("Diagram 1-1 (up to S5g) is from one of the most popular openings: static Rook vs ranging Rook.")
B.Lv=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1grs2/1pppp1bpp/p4pp2/7P1/P1P1P1P2/1P1PSP2P/1BK1GS1R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-1")
B.ajW=new A.c('Black, with the static Rook, is setting up for a quick attack. White, on the other hand, has formed a Mino-castle with two Golds and a Silver. Black will then play S4f, reinforcing his attack. This may seem at odds with "three generals\' defence," but in this case the Silver on 4h is regarded as part of the defence.\n')
B.Nc=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1grs2/1pppp1bpp/p4pp2/7P1/P1P1P4/1PBP1PP1P/1KS1GS1R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-2")
B.amx=new A.c("Diagram 1-2 (up to S-7h) shows the beginning of a slow game, where the static Rook side has built up the left Mino-castle, vying with White's sturdy guard.")
B.akM=new A.c("In a ranging-against-static-Rook game, the right half of the board (where the Rooks sit) is likely to become the battlefield, rather than making direct attack against each King.")
B.M3=new A.p("l2g3nl/1ks2r3/1png2bp1/2pppsp1p/p4p1P1/2PPP1P1P/PP1GSPN2/LS1B3R1/KNG5L b -","Diagram 1-3")
B.alK=new A.c("Diagram 1-3 (up to S-4d) represents Black's anaguma with the static Rook. The Gold on 6g prepares for the future attack from the mid-area.")
B.NJ=new A.p("l2g3nl/1ks4r1/1png1sbp1/2p1ppp1p/p2p3P1/2P1P1P1P/PPSP1P3/LSGB3R1/KNG4NL w -","Diagram 1-4")
B.ain=new A.c("Diagram 1-4 (up to S-7g) is the absolute in anaguma castles, with four generals. This does not violate the three-generals guideline but makes even more sturdy defence, maybe a little too sturdy. You need to improvise when you want to attack with such scanty pieces for offence.")
B.a1y=A.a(s([B.agI,B.agl,B.Lv,B.ajW,B.Nc,B.amx,B.akM,B.M3,B.alK,B.NJ,B.ain]),t.A)
B.ac3=new A.ar(B.a1y)
B.alm=new A.c("Next we will look into a typical double-static-Rook opening.")
B.M7=new A.p("l6nl/1r3bgk1/p1ns1gspp/2ppppp2/1p5P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-1")
B.ah4=new A.c("In Diagram 2-1, both players have exactly the same position with three Generals in defence and RBSN in offence. Both are in good shape. An intense battle is expected to ensue from here.")
B.LL=new A.p("ln5nl/1r3sgk1/p1bp1gspp/2p1ppp2/1p5P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-2")
B.aig=new A.c("In Diagram 2-2 (up to S4b), Black's fortress is the same as above while White employs all the generals for defence. The Bishop on 7c functions to restrain Black's deployment rather than aiming at a direct attack. This again is too defence-oriented, and I would not advise you to employ it.")
B.MB=new A.p("l5knl/1r2g1g2/2n1p1sp1/p1ppspp1p/1p5P1/P1PPSPP1P/1PS1P1N2/2G1G2R1/LNK5L b Bb","Diagram 2-3")
B.ahT=new A.c("Diagram 2-3 (up to N7c) shows both camps having the same position, the Bishop-exchange with the reclining Silver in this case. The Silver above the Pawn on 5th file is called the reclining Silver. With this position, a fierce battle seems to be imminent, since the Bishop is in hand instead of sitting on the board. This should yield wider variety of offence.")
B.ahu=new A.c("Proceeding from the position in the diagram, Black will play P-4e, followed by Px4e, P-3e. Ideally Black should play K-8h or G-6h before opening the attack. Modern joseki teaches us, however, that procrastination is very costly in this position.")
B.Nj=new A.p("lr4knl/5ggb1/2n1ps1p1/p1ppspp1p/9/PPP1SPPRP/1S1PP1N2/1BGG5/LNK5L b Pp","Diagram 2-4")
B.aiD=new A.c("In Diagram 2-4 (up to R8a), both players have taken the Aigakari opening, which includes Pawn-exchange in the Rook files. From here Black can play P-3e, Px3e, P-4e. For White's part, the position is a tad on the defensive, but playing S-6e is a possibility.")
B.TB=A.a(s([B.alm,B.M7,B.ah4,B.LL,B.aig,B.MB,B.ahT,B.ahu,B.Nj,B.aiD]),t.A)
B.adb=new A.ar(B.TB)
B.ak5=new A.c("Finally, some positions from the double-ranging-Rook opening. In this opening, the opponent's attacking pieces are aiming at the head of your King, so your castle had better be well-prepared for an attack from above.")
B.Lx=new A.p("ln6l/1skgg4/1pppp1n1b/p4pr1p/1P1P2sp1/PRPBS3P/2N1PPPP1/4GGKS1/L6NL b p","Diagram 3-1")
B.adD=new A.c("Diagram 3-1 (up to B1c) is a typical double-ranging-Rook opening called Kin-Muso, or Two-Piece-Gold. Incidentally, this includes typically bad shape called the wall-Silver, but is strong against an attack from above, nonetheless.")
B.Ow=new A.p("ln6l/1skggr3/1pppp1n2/p4psbp/1P1P3p1/PRPBSPP1P/2N1PGSP1/5GK2/L6NL w p","Diagram 3-2")
B.aes=new A.c("In Diagram 3-2 (up to N7g), Black has taken the Yagura castle instead of the Kin-Muso. Remember Yagura is also the right castle when playing the double-ranging-Rook. Compared with the Kin-Muso, the notorious wall-Silver is no longer there, so your King should enjoy more breathing space.")
B.L3=new A.p("kn6l/lsgg1r3/ppppp1n2/5psbp/1PPP3p1/PR1BSPP1P/2N1PGSP1/6GK1/L6NL w p","Diagram 3-3")
B.ajH=new A.c("In Diagram 3-3 (up to N7g), Black has built the Yagura, while White has ensconced the King in the anaguma castle. Note that the Golds are on 6b and 7b, which makes an anomalous anaguma castle. Anaguma's Golds are normally on 7a and 7b. Two Golds side-by-side is a countermeasure against the attack from above when playing double-ranging-Rook. Three Generals should make a good defence, but their placement differs from position to position.")
B.Ly=new A.p("ln1g4l/1ks1g4/1pppsp1p1/p4br2/1SPPp2np/PR1B5/2N1PPPPP/5SG2/L3G1KNL b Pp","Diagram 3-4")
B.adN=new A.c("White in Diagram 3-4 (up to N2e) has built the Mino-castle. However, as far as the double-ranging-Rook is concerned, the Mino is not a very good defence. Incidentally, Black's King is not very safe, either, with his vulnerable right edge.")
B.a3Y=A.a(s([B.ak5,B.Lx,B.adD,B.Ow,B.aes,B.L3,B.ajH,B.Ly,B.adN]),t.A)
B.adl=new A.ar(B.a3Y)
B.a_b=A.a(s([B.ac3,B.adb,B.adl]),t.l)
B.ao7=new A.bf(20,B.bs,"Defend the King with three Generals, Attack with Rook, Bishop, Silver and Knight","Gyoku no mamori wa Kin Gin 3 mai, seme wa Hi, Kaku, Gin, Kei",B.a_b)
B.ajn=new A.c("So long as you see the castle as a space secured for your King, you should push the edge Pawn thereby making more room for the King to breathe. However, if the opponent has also built up the Yagura castle, the opponent's attacking pieces will therefore be at your King's head. You may invite a premature clash by advancing the edge Pawn. So, do be careful. This is what the proverb teaches.")
B.Mr=new A.p("ln5nl/1r1s1bgk1/3p1gspp/ppp1ppp2/9/2PPP1PP1/PPSG1PN1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 1-1")
B.alU=new A.c("If you play P9f in Diagram 1-1, there will follow:")
B.XI=A.a(s(["P9f","P8e","P4f","S7c"]),t.s)
B.a8B=new A.Q(null,B.XI,B.j)
B.Ok=new A.p("ln5nl/1r3bgk1/2sp1gspp/p1p1ppp2/1p7/P1PPPPPP1/1PSG2N1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 1-2")
B.ajI=new A.c("If you push up your edge Pawn in the same file as your opponent did his, you may let a fight start on the left wing. When you play White, S7c is a move to play after Black has played P9f.")
B.Yr=A.a(s(["S4g","S8d","P2e"]),t.s)
B.a9F=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 1-2:",B.Yr,B.j)
B.aiw=new A.c("Both sides have paved their way to begin an attack, but you should note that White is a step ahead because of Black's P9f.")
B.a_U=A.a(s(["P9e","Px9e","Sx9e","Lx9e","Lx9e"]),t.s)
B.a99=new A.Q("Then there will follow:",B.a_U,B.u)
B.Lb=new A.p("1n5nl/1r3bgk1/3p1gspp/2p1ppp2/lp5P1/2PPPPP2/1PSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/1N6L b SPlp","Diagram 1-3")
B.ajo=new A.c("See the price Black has to pay just because he hasn't observed the proverb. White's Sx9e is what you should remember when attacking the edge file with the Bo-gin.")
B.ahN=new A.c("From Diagram 1-3, White can play R9b or P*9g, while Black is far from being comfortable having a skirmish started quite close to his King.")
B.RM=A.a(s([B.ajn,B.Mr,B.alU,B.a8B,B.Ok,B.ajI,B.a9F,B.aiw,B.a99,B.Lb,B.ajo,B.ahN]),t.A)
B.acS=new A.ar(B.RM)
B.akI=new A.c("What if you don't play P9f in Diagram 1-1?")
B.a3y=A.a(s(["P4f","P9e","S4g","N7c","P2e"]),t.s)
B.aac=new A.Q(null,B.a3y,B.j)
B.OC=new A.p("l6nl/1r1s1bgk1/2np1gspp/1pp1ppp2/p6P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L w -","Diagram 2-1")
B.aeo=new A.c("By not playing P9f in response to P9d, you have managed to keep White's attacking pieces at bay. You have allowed him to advance his edge Pawn to 9e instead, but Diagram 1-2 shows that you are the one to go first.")
B.aja=new A.c("Again back in Diagram 1-1, what if White resorts to the Bo-gin?")
B.X7=A.a(s(["P4f","P8e","S4g","S7c","P2e","S8d"]),t.s)
B.a9T=new A.Q(null,B.X7,B.j)
B.LJ=new A.p("ln5nl/1r3bgk1/3p1gspp/psp1ppp2/1p5P1/2PPPPP2/PPSG1SN1P/1KGB3R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-2")
B.afO=new A.c("You have nothing to worry about. When White plays S9e, you can chase it away by P9f. Also in this position, you are the one to take the initiative.")
B.adV=new A.c("Lastly, let me add the position in which you can play the edge Pawn. If White's Knight is on 7c at an early stage, as in Diagram 2-3, you can safely play P9f. In other words, as long as it's certain that White does not employ the Bo-gin, you can play P9f after White's P9d.")
B.M9=new A.p("l6nl/1r1s1bgk1/2np1gspp/ppp1ppp2/9/2PPP1PP1/PPSG1PN1P/1KGB1S1R1/LN6L b -","Diagram 2-3")
B.amL=new A.c("This is my personal opinion, but when you play the double fortress opening, it is better to play something for the future offense rather than playing the defensive move (P9f in response to P9d).")
B.a29=A.a(s([B.akI,B.aac,B.OC,B.aeo,B.aja,B.a9T,B.LJ,B.afO,B.adV,B.M9,B.amL]),t.A)
B.acw=new A.ar(B.a29)
B.a4j=A.a(s([B.acS,B.acw]),t.l)
B.aoP=new A.bf(21,B.bs,"In the Yagura Opening, Don't Push the Edge Pawn","Yagura-gakoi ni hashi-fu wo tsukuna",B.a4j)
B.amn=new A.c("The edge Pawn in the Mino-castle could play a crucial role. When your opponent plays P1d as in Diagram 1, you'd best respond with P1f. Later on the square of 1g will mean a great deal for your King.")
B.Mi=new A.p("8l/9/7p1/6p1p/9/9/5PPPP/4G1SK1/5G1NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.aeX=new A.c("Had your opponent's Pawn come to 9e, as in Diagram 2, and if your Gold on 6a were taken, your King will be mated in three moves: S*7a, K-9b, G*8b.")
B.Lz=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/ppp6/9/P8/2P6/1P7/9/L8 b GS","Diagram 2")
B.agO=new A.c("In Diagram 3, however, Black will need four Generals to mate the King.")
B.Lw=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/1pp6/p8/9/P1P6/1P7/9/L8 b 2G2S","Diagram 3")
B.XN=A.a(s(["S*7a","K9b","G*9c","Kx9c","S*8b","K9b","Sx9a+","K9c","S8b-","Kx8b","G*9b"]),t.s)
B.a9M=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 3:",B.XN,B.j)
B.aj7=new A.c("You should not drop a Gold on 9b as in Diagram 2. The King will then sit on 9c, and you won't be able to check any further.")
B.aie=new A.c("Compare those two diagrams above and see what a difference an edge Pawn can make when the King is in the Mino-castle. The edge square secured by pushing up a Pawn was worth two Generals in this case.")
B.OO=new A.p("ln1+P5/1ks6/1pp6/9/p8/2P6/PP7/9/L8 b 3G3S","Diagram 4")
B.adL=new A.c("What if the edge Pawn was another square ahead (Diagram 4)? In order to mate White's King, you will need as many as six Generals.")
B.YS=A.a(s(["S*7a","K-9b","G*9c","Kx9c","S*8b","K-9d","S*8e","Kx8e","G*7e","K-9d","G*8e"]),t.s)
B.aay=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 4:",B.YS,B.j)
B.afw=new A.c("If, after the 5th move in the above, White plays K9b, it will be even quicker: G*9c, Nx9c, Sx9a+, Kx9a, G*8b.")
B.akC=new A.c("Now I hope I have made it clear that pushing up the edge Pawn, which is a part of the Mino-castle, can earn a lot: each square gained means two Generals.")
B.ai5=new A.c("When you build up the Mino-castle, don't forget to push up the edge Pawn. You won't regret it, especially toward the endgame.")
B.ZQ=A.a(s([B.amn,B.Mi,B.aeX,B.Lz,B.agO,B.Lw,B.a9M,B.aj7,B.aie,B.OO,B.adL,B.aay,B.afw,B.akC,B.ai5]),t.A)
B.acb=new A.ar(B.ZQ)
B.a3X=A.a(s([B.acb]),t.l)
B.aov=new A.bf(22,B.bs,"Push up the Edge Pawn When Playing the Mino Castle","Mino-gakoi wa hashifu wo tsuke",B.a3X)
B.all=new A.c("Before you begin to build up your castle, be sure to look at your opponent's camp as well as yours. Pay attention, above all, where the opponent's Bishop sits. Placing your King on the Bishop's diagonal can be very dangerous.")
B.Ox=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p1n1pp1pp/1ppps1p2/9/2PPP4/PPSG1PPPP/1KGB1S1R1/LN5NL w -","Diagram 1")
B.afF=new A.c("Diagram 1 shows where Black has played K-8h, in the Yagura castle: a normal move, apparently. But it turned out to be a bad move, since the King moved into a dangerous zone.")
B.Xd=A.a(s(["N8e","S8f","P6e"]),t.s)
B.a8e=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 1:",B.Xd,B.u)
B.NV=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p3pp1pp/1pp1s1p2/1n1p5/1SPPP4/PP1G1PPPP/1KGB1S1R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 2")
B.agV=new A.c("N8e is a smart move on White's part. Naturally Black avoids offering his Silver in exchange for a Knight; therefore, he plays S8f, but White's next move, P6e, gives Black a headache. Black cannot play Px6e.")
B.Ys=A.a(s(["S5g","Px6f","Sx6f","S6e"]),t.s)
B.a8x=new A.Q("Moves thereafter:",B.Ys,B.j)
B.LO=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sgb1/p3pp1pp/1pp3p2/1n1s5/1SPSP4/PP1G1PPPP/1KGB3R1/LN5NL b Pp","Diagram 3")
B.aiW=new A.c("In Diagram 3, Black is already in a losing position.")
B.ajl=new A.c("Back in Diagram 1 where White is ready to attack from the 6th file, Black should have built a different type of castle, like the one in Diagram 4 (last move N7c). You don't have to stick to the authentic Yagura castle at all times. Even if you cannot complete the castle and leave it as in Diagram 4, it does not mean that you are in a bad position.")
B.KG=new A.p("l2g2knl/3r1sg2/p1n1ppbpp/1ppps1p2/7P1/2PPP1P2/PP1GSP2P/1BGS3R1/LNK4NL b -","Diagram 4")
B.ael=new A.c("As a guideline, you should remember, unless there are two pieces or more that are interposed between the Bishop and your King, it won't be safe to place your King in the Bishop's diagonal. You should note, however, in case those interposed pieces are sure to be attacked, for instance by White's N8e and P6e as in Diagram 1, it is not at all safe. Don't forget that the Bishop's diagonal can be quite dangerous for your King.")
B.a2d=A.a(s([B.all,B.Ox,B.afF,B.a8e,B.NV,B.agV,B.a8x,B.LO,B.aiW,B.ajl,B.KG,B.ael]),t.A)
B.ac5=new A.ar(B.a2d)
B.VC=A.a(s([B.ac5]),t.l)
B.aog=new A.bf(23,B.bs,"Don't Put the King on the Bishop's Diagonal","Gyoku wa Kaku-suji wo sakeyo",B.VC)
B.al0=new A.c("Depending on which Pawns are pushed in the opening, the future strategy varies. Diagram 1 (last move P6d) shows where Black has aligned his Pawns in the fourth row along the 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th and 9th file, quite observant of the proverb in question. As a matter of fact, this formation will work best in a quick attack scheme with the Rook in its original position.")
B.Os=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbp1/p2p1pp1p/7P1/P1P1P1P1P/1P1PSP3/1BKGGS1R1/LN5NL b -","Diagram 1")
B.als=new A.c("For the sake of argument, see the position below where Pawns in the even number files are all a square ahead. You can see how problematic it is for the Bishop to be effective. This explains the idea behind the proverb.")
B.L9=new A.p("9/9/9/9/9/1P1P1P1P1/P1P1P1P1P/1B7/9 b -","Diagram 2")
B.af1=new A.c("When the game becomes slow, you are likely to push up other Pawns as well, like Diagram 3 (last move B2f). But remember, odd number first, then even number. This is the general idea.")
B.LF=new A.p("ln3r1nl/1kg6/1s1g1sbp1/ppppppp1p/7P1/PPPPPPPBP/1S1GS4/1KG4R1/LN5NL w -","Diagram 3")
B.ahE=new A.c("Also in the Yagura opening, you first play with the odd-number file Pawns. See Diagram 4 (last move P7d) how both Bishops are threatening each other camp with the 3rd, 5th and 7th file Pawns neatly positioned for their Bishops to pass.")
B.LY=new A.p("ln3kbnl/1r1sg1g2/p2p2spp/1pp1ppp2/9/2PPP1P2/PPSG1P1PP/2G2S1R1/LNBK3NL b -","Diagram 4")
B.aiE=new A.c("Needless to say, the proverb is not against the advancement of the Pawns in the even-number files at all times.")
B.R6=A.a(s([B.al0,B.Os,B.als,B.L9,B.af1,B.LF,B.ahE,B.LY,B.aiE]),t.A)
B.acg=new A.ar(B.R6)
B.Y3=A.a(s([B.acg]),t.l)
B.aoh=new A.bf(24,B.bs,"In the Opening Push up Pawns in the Odd-number Files","Joban wa kisuu no Fu wo tsuke",B.Y3)
B.adR=new A.c("Suppose your Pawn is on the f-rank directly opposite your opponent's Pawn on the d-rank, then the threat is even. Neither side has a kurai. But if yours is on the e-rank preventing the opponent's Pawn to advance further, you have a kurai in that file. Taking a kurai means to restrict the opponent's moves. But sometimes it can be a target at which your opponent makes an attack.")
B.aly=new A.c("The proverb above teaches that you should not only hold the vanguard Pawn steady, but make sure it won't be a target from your opponent.")
B.NN=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbpp/p2p1pp2/4P2P1/P1P1SPP2/1P1P4P/1BKSG2R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-1")
B.aeJ=new A.c("Diagram 1-1 shows where Black has just played to support the Pawn on 5e (called the 5e-kurai-dori) against White's ranging Rook opening.")
B.afE=new A.c("Diagram 1-2 is called gyoku-to-kurai-dori (King's head kurai-dori), where Black has played S7f to the same effect.")
B.M6=new A.p("ln1g3nl/1ks1gr3/1pp1psbpp/p2p1pp2/2P1P2P1/P1S6/1P1PSPP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL w -","Diagram 1-2")
B.aip=new A.c("Please note that in both cases a Silver goes up to support the Pawn on e. The Silver is the most suitable reinforcing piece on the front.")
B.amz=new A.c("Look again at both Diagrams. See that even if White tries a counterattack against the vanguard Pawn, Black can summon another Silver to the front in just one move.")
B.ahf=new A.c("One more thing about a kurai. Look at Diagram 1-3.")
B.KW=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2P1P4/2SPS2P1/PP3PP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL b -","Diagram 1-3")
B.aef=new A.c("Black has two kurai's here, but that's simply too good to get away with. You will end up incurring heaps of troubles trying to keep those two footholds, unless you have the position like one below (Diagram 1-4), where the kurai's are side by side, on top of two Silvers placed close-by. That's only when your two kurai's work.")
B.MY=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2PP5/2SSP2P1/PP3PP1P/1BK1G2R1/LN1G3NL b -","Diagram 1-4")
