B.a1k=A.a(s([B.ad9,B.ade,B.ach,B.ac_]),t.l)
B.aox=new A.bf(45,B.ew,"Drop where your opponent wants to drop","teki no uchitai tokoro e ute",B.a1k)
B.am7=new A.c("Major pieces, namely Rooks and Bishops, are most effective when they threaten from afar. In a clash at close quarters, however, they are sometimes forced to draw back in order not to be taken by less valuable pieces. You can take advantage of this characteristic in defense.")
B.LA=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2P1b4/9/PP7/1KG6/LNB6 b SPp","Diagram 1-1")
B.akE=new A.c("In Diagram 1-1, White has just checked Black's King with B5e. How would you defend here? S*7g would invite White's P*7f. So you should play...?")
B.a4l=A.a(s(["P*6f"]),t.s)
B.a9v=new A.Q(null,B.a4l,B.j)
B.MT=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2P1b4/3P5/PP7/1KG6/LNB6 b SPp","Diagram 1-2")
B.afP=new A.c('This is called the "mid-interposition". Unless you know the idea, the move should be hard to come up with.')
B.a0F=A.a(s(["Bx6f","S*7g"]),t.s)
B.a9W=new A.Q("Moves after Diagram 1-2:",B.a0F,B.u)
B.OD=new A.p("9/9/9/9/2P6/3b5/PPS6/1KG6/LNB6 w 2p","Diagram 1-3")
B.aj0=new A.c("By sacrificing one Pawn, you can scare the Bishop away. After White moves his Bishop to a safe square, you will have your turn, which can make a big difference, especially in the endgame.")
B.afa=new A.c("Let the big piece draw near, so that you can take the initiative. Once you have learned this, it should help you greatly in actual games.")
B.VR=A.a(s([B.am7,B.LA,B.akE,B.a9v,B.MT,B.afP,B.a9W,B.OD,B.aj0,B.afa]),t.A)
B.adx=new A.ar(B.VR)
B.NM=new A.p("8l/9/9/9/4b2pp/9/5PPPP/4G1SK1/4BG1NL b 2gn","Diagram 2-1")
B.agv=new A.c("In Diagram 2-1 (last move B5e), Black is being attacked at the weak spot in the Mino castle. If left unattended, White will play N*3f...mate. If Black plays K3i for an early escape, G*2h will do the job. Even if Black plays K4h after this, N*5f, K5g, G*6f (mate).")
B.agU=new A.c("If Black has anything in hand to drop on 4f, that would make the castle sturdy, but he has no piece in hand. Then what should Black play?")
B.XC=A.a(s(["P4f"]),t.s)
B.a9h=new A.Q(null,B.XC,B.j)
B.aiI=new A.c("The move may seem like a waste of time, but in fact it is far from it.")
B.Uu=A.a(s(["Bx4f","G4g"]),t.s)
B.aah=new A.Q("Moves thereafter:",B.Uu,B.u)
B.LQ=new A.p("8l/9/9/9/7pp/5b3/5GPPP/6SK1/4BG1NL w 2gnp","Diagram 2-2")
B.aiS=new A.c("After Bx4g, it is still threatmate for Black, but G4g at once claims the Bishop and defends the 3f square.")
B.akO=new A.c("For those who like to play the ranging Rook, this tesuji will come in handy.")
B.a3u=A.a(s([B.NM,B.agv,B.agU,B.a9h,B.aiI,B.aah,B.LQ,B.aiS,B.akO]),t.A)
B.adn=new A.ar(B.a3u)
B.Nd=new A.p("ln7/1ks1+P+R3/ppppp4/5p3/2G6/2P6/PPN6/1K3+r3/L8 b GPs","Diagram 3-1")
B.ahF=new A.c("Above is a partial diagram in the endgame. How should Black play to win this game? At present, though, Black has to respond to the check. K8i will be followed by S*8h, K9h, Sx7g+ (mate). K7i won't do, either (from S*7h). So he has to drop something to interpose. G*7h, the most commonplace, will allow S*6g (Diagram 3-A), after which White will be able to continue his attack.")
B.NE=new A.p("ln7/1ks1+P+R3/ppppp4/5p3/2G6/2P6/PPNs5/1KG2+r3/L8 b P","Diagram 3-A")
B.amN=new A.c("After Diagram 3-A, Black could play P*6h, but White will then respond with Sx6h+, which is a good move. Then there will follow Gx6h, +Rx6h, S*7h, G*6g (Diagram 3-B). In Diagram 3-B, Black is defenseless.")
B.Mq=new A.p("ln7/1ks1+P+R3/ppppp4/5p3/2G6/2P6/PPNg5/1KS+r5/L8 b p","Diagram 3-B")
B.aix=new A.c("On the other hand in White's camp, if Black can only play +P6b, White's King will have no defense. In order for Black to win, he has to contrive to earn time. A commonplace defense won't do. So...?")
B.Sm=A.a(s(["P*6h"]),t.s)
B.a9q=new A.Q(null,B.Sm,B.j)
B.ae3=new A.c("The proverb will be a big help.")
B.a0P=A.a(s(["+Rx6h","G*7h"]),t.s)
B.a8w=new A.Q("Moves thereafter:",B.a0P,B.u)
B.ND=new A.p("ln7/1ks1+P+R3/ppppp4/5p3/2G6/2P6/PPN6/1KG+r5/L8 w sp","Diagram 3-2")
B.ahK=new A.c("From Diagram 3-2, if White plays +R5h, Black can play the aforementioned +P6h to finish the game. If White plays S*7i, K8i will be scary but alright.")
B.af9=new A.c("Remember, taking the initiative can be crucial in the endgame. By drawing the big piece closer and then repel it, you will be able to take the initiative.")
B.a1F=A.a(s([B.Nd,B.ahF,B.NE,B.amN,B.Mq,B.aix,B.a9q,B.ae3,B.a8w,B.ND,B.ahK,B.af9]),t.A)
B.adq=new A.ar(B.a1F)
B.O0=new A.p("lnsgk1snl/1r4gb1/p1ppppppp/9/9/PpP4R1/3PPPP1P/1BG6/LNS1KGSNL b 2P","Diagram 4-1")
B.af7=new A.c("Lastly I would like you to note that this tesuji is not only meant for the endgame. Diagram 4-1 is from the twisting Rook opening, where White has just dropped a dangling Pawn on 8f. In order to cope with the coming P8g+, Black has three means:")
B.alB=new A.c("1) Support the 8g square with one more piece.\n2) Reduce the opponent's effective power on 8g.\n3) Play an even more damaging move to White than P8g+ does to Black.\n")
B.ai_=new A.c("At the moment, Black has only one choice available: 2).")
B.aiB=new A.c("P*8d is the move that meets the idea taught by proverb. Then there will follow: Rx8d, B6f, R8b, S8h. (Diagram 4-A)")
B.MK=new A.p("lnsgk1snl/1r4gb1/p1ppppppp/9/9/PpPB3R1/3PPPP1P/1SG6/LN2KGSNL w Pp","Diagram 4-A")
B.aet=new A.c("Indeed Black has managed to prevent the damage that P8g+ would bring, but has lost one Pawn in the process. What is worse, Black cannot take the Pawn on 8f anytime soon. So, that was not a successful defense.")
B.YU=A.a(s(["P*8e","Rx8e","N7g","R8b","P*8e"]),t.s)
B.a8R=new A.Q("Moves after Diagram 4-1:",B.YU,B.j)
B.LK=new A.p("lnsgk1snl/1r4gb1/p1ppppppp/9/1P7/PpP4R1/3PPPP1P/1BG6/LNS1KGSNL w P","Diagram 4-2")
B.Yt=A.a(s(["S6b","P7e","P6d","Rx8f"]),t.s)
B.a9J=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 4-2:",B.Yt,B.u)
B.Nv=new A.p("ln1gk1snl/1r1s2gb1/p1p1ppppp/3p5/1PP6/PR7/2NPPPP1P/1BG6/L1S1KGSNL w Pp","Diagram 4-3")
B.agX=new A.c("P*8e is what Black should play. Playing N7g gives him the initiative, and in Diagram 4-3 Black has taken a Pawn back. The position here is promising for Black.")
B.a2n=A.a(s([B.O0,B.af7,B.alB,B.ai_,B.aiB,B.MK,B.aet,B.a8R,B.LK,B.a9J,B.Nv,B.agX]),t.A)
B.acH=new A.ar(B.a2n)
B.Vi=A.a(s([B.adx,B.adn,B.adq,B.acH]),t.l)
B.aoi=new A.bf(46,B.ew,"Defend against major pieces by drawing them closer","Oo-goma wa chikazukete ukeyo",B.Vi)
B.anc=new A.c("When two of your pieces are attacked by one enemy piece with the same move, you cannot save both. This is not an uncommon situation when you play a quick attack opening like Yokofu-dori. The idea conveyed in the above proverb is: Don't just think of rescuing one of the threatened pieces, but consider the position in a positive light.")
B.am9=new A.c("Look at Diagram 1-1 (last move B*5e). This is one of the possible positions you might run into when playing Yokofu-dori.")
B.LV=new A.p("lnsgk2nl/6g2/p1pppps1p/9/4b4/6P2/P2PPP2P/2G4S1/LNS1KG1NL b RB3Pr3p","Diagram 1-1")
B.amW=new A.c("You are Black. Your next move is?\nG-3h? No, you'll lose a Lance on 9i.\nS-8h? No, you'll lose a Silver on 2h.\nP*8b. Yes, that's the only way to put the proverb to good use.\n")
B.Vf=A.a(s(["Bx2h+","Px8a+","S-6b","P*7b"]),t.s)
B.a8X=new A.Q("The most likely moves thereafter would be:",B.Vf,B.u)
B.KV=new A.p("l+P1gk2nl/2Ps2g2/p1pppps1p/9/9/6P2/P2PPP2P/2G4+b1/LNS1KG1NL w RBNPrs3p","Diagram 1-2")
B.ahW=new A.c("Here the position is even. When in ryo-dori, the obvious first choice should be saving one of the pieces, which is often the right move. But sometimes you may come up with a better idea. This is what the proverb is teaching.")
B.a2_=A.a(s([B.anc,B.am9,B.LV,B.amW,B.a8X,B.KV,B.ahW]),t.A)
B.ace=new A.ar(B.a2_)
B.amy=new A.c("Now let me show you how the idea was applied in a real game. Look at Diagram 2-1. White just dropped a Bishop on 3i, forking a Rook and a Gold. R-2f will be out of the question because it would only allow the Bishop to take a Gold and and promote on 6f. Worse yet, it is ote(mate). R*4h would rescue both pieces indeed, but it would only make White gloat knowing you can't attack with a meager paratroop.")
B.Ni=new A.p("ln4knl/4g1g2/3sp1spp/p4p3/6SP1/PG1GP4/5P2P/1K1B3R1/LN4bNL b R6Ps2p","Diagram 2-1")
B.Y2=A.a(s(["R*7a","S*4a","P*3d","S-2b"]),t.s)
B.a9w=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 2-1:",B.Y2,B.j)
B.Oz=new A.p("lnR2sknl/4g1gs1/3sp2pp/p4pP2/6SP1/PG1GP4/5P2P/1K1B3R1/LN4bNL b 5P2p","Diagram 2-2")
B.afQ=new A.c("Black didn't run from a fork, but went on to attack. White's idea was to maintain material advantage, so he tried to steer toward a long and slow game...")
B.a1l=A.a(s(["P*6d","S-5d","P-5e","Bx2h+","Px5d"]),t.s)
B.a91=new A.Q("Moves from Diagram 2-2:",B.a1l,B.j)
B.KQ=new A.p("lnR2sknl/4g1gs1/4p2pp/p2PPpP2/6SP1/PG1G5/5P2P/1K1B3+b1/LN5NL w S4Pr2p","Diagram 2-3")
B.afI=new A.c("In response to the third move, P-5e, White didn't play S-4c. If he had, Black's R-2f would have been just the right defense. If White had played Bx6f+, Black would have responded with B-7g, which would make a great difference compared with a position where Black played R-2f in the first place.")
B.ak6=new A.c("Diagram 2-3 shows both parties in equilibrium. Compare it with Diagram 2-1 where Black's Rook and Gold are forked, which you might well consider a crisis. Black played deftly, put the proverb into practice and got himself out of trouble.")
